 into firsthand contact with the natural world. The aim was simple but revolutionary: sympathy with nature to increase the joy of living and foster stewardship of the earth.With this definitive edition, John Linstrom reintroduces The Nature-Study Idea as an environmental classic for our time. It provides historical context through a wealth of related writings, and introductory essays relate Bailey's vision to current work in education and the intersection of climate change and culture. In this period of planetary turmoil, Bailey's ambition to cultivate wonder (in adults as well as children) and lead readers back into the natural world is more important than ever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aNature study. 4aEDUCATION & HISTORY OF EDUCATION. 4aENVIRONMENT. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh  aprogressive reform, environmental education, ecospheric imagination, Liberty Hyde Bailey, ecological philosophy, natural history teaching, child-centered curriculum.1 aBailey, L. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinstrom, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinstrom, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOrr, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Dilafruz R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501772627zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501772627zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com